public interface IExpressionInterpreter<T extends IExpression>

Interface definition of the IExpression interpreters. Every implementation of an IExpression interpreter is specialized to interpret an instance of IExpression. During the querying process the generated parser tree containing a tree-structured representation of the query will be interpreted incremental.

An Instance of IExpression will be an argument of the interpretation process of a IExpressionInterpreter which will be instantiate by the InterpreterRegistryImpl.

Author:
Sven Krosse

Method returns a list of all interpreters for the sub-expression of the internal expression. If the expression is a leaf this method will return an empty list of interpreters. The method instantiate one interpreter for each expression by calling the InterpreterRegistryImpl:

containsExpressionsType

boolean containsExpressionsType(java.lang.Class<? extends IExpression> type)
                                throws TMQLRuntimeException
Method checks if the internal expression has at least one child-node of the given expression type.

The method is useful because of the fact that some sub-expression are optional like a where-clause of a select-expression.

Parameters:
type - the type to look for
Returns:
true if the expression has at least one child-node of the given type, false otherwise.
Throws:
TMQLRuntimeException - thrown if operation fails.

getGrammarTypeOfExpression

int getGrammarTypeOfExpression()
In the current draft some production rules support different syntactical patterns and can be differ in grammar levels. The method return an identifier representing the grammar type at the context of the production rule.

Returns:
a numeric value representing the grammar type

getTypeOfExpression

java.lang.Class<T> getTypeOfExpression()
The current draft specify a number of different production rules. Each of this production rules is represented by an instance of IExpression and so there are an instance of IExpressionInterpreter for each type of IExpression.

This method will return the type of the expression which can be handled by this IExpressionInterpreter instance.

Returns:
a class object of the supported expression type
